I&#39;ve only just begun to look at using JUnit, however I have a lot of 
experience with automating GUI tests.

I should introduce myself a little - I work for the Java SW Division 
of Sun (or whatever the official name for Javasoft is nowadays), 
developing test tools and test suites in the group that tests the 
&quot;client aspects&quot; of J2SE (the software package previously known as 
&quot;The JDK&quot;).  I had a hand in creating the java.awt.Robot class (this 
email address is my personal email).

In our team we widely use Robot for GUI automation.  We do, though, 
have different requirements than most since we are testing the JDK as 
it is being developed, rather than testing an application built using 
the shipping JDK.  I gave a brief talk last week at a JavaOne BOF 
about what we&#39;re doing for GUI test automation.

The glance I&#39;ve taken at JUnit so far tells me it&#39;s a framework to 
help creating test cases, and that there&#39;s nothing in it to aid GUI 
automation.  We&#39;ve created a few different similar frameworks in our 
test suites here, and I can tell you that at the level I see JUnit 
operating, that use of Robot fits in very well.  Also, that if you 
choose to use Robot, that you will need to develop some higher level 
code to provide higher level functionality.

We have gotten a lot of mileage out of validation through looking at 
internal state.  Primarily this boils down to listening to listener 
interfaces, and saying that the test passes if the right listeners 
are called.

- David Herron

&gt;
&gt;It isn&#39;t a question of being favorable or not.  It is a question of &quot;Do you
&gt;want to automate the testing of your GUI with JUnit?  And if so, to what
&gt;granularity?&quot;  I think testing the GUI is always good, but there are
&gt;limitations for JUnit to do this.  If there is pertinent state information
&gt;that you want to capture (which it doesn&#39;t sound like there is) you can use
&gt;the approach I mentioned before.  If you simply want to test the overall
&gt;look, a one-eyed inspection is fine.  If you want to programmatically test
&gt;the overall look, something like SilkTest would probably be a good way to
&gt;go.  I think that having state inspectors on every GUI component is
&gt;overkill!  If there is some meta-state that your controller gets from the
&gt;view to effect a change on your model, then write an inspector on your
&gt;controller for that, but not just for testing.  The test should reflect (to
&gt;some degree) the usage.  Again, this isn&#39;t a silver bullet, it&#39;s just one
&gt;example.
&gt;
&gt;MVC can be difficult.  If it is done improperly it offers many traps!!  But
&gt;done rightly, it&#39;s a wonderful tool.  Testing is easier, refactoring is
&gt;easier, etc.
&gt;
&gt;-Jason
&gt;

-- 
